    <entry>
      <title>递归</title>
      <link href="/2023/04/01/SICP%E2%80%94%E2%80%94%E9%80%92%E5%BD%92%E7%9A%84%E5%A6%99%E7%94%A8/"/>
      <url>/2023/04/01/SICP%E2%80%94%E2%80%94%E9%80%92%E5%BD%92%E7%9A%84%E5%A6%99%E7%94%A8/</url>
      
        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<h1 id="recursion">Recursion</h1><h2 id="structure-and-interpretation-of-computer-programs">Structure andInterpretation of Computer Programs</h2><p>Good morning! Today, I want to talk something about recursion. Beforethat, I would say that computer sciencs is a branch of mathematics.</p><p><strong>So what is recursion?</strong></p><p>Okay, if you want to understand recursion, you should first knowabout what is recursion. The progress is just like peeling an onion andrestoring it. (However, I think this progress what we learn is hard tosolve it.)</p><blockquote><p>I like a Chinese story and I think it can be used to interpret whatis recursion:从前有座山，山中有座庙，庙里有个老和尚，老和尚在给小和尚讲故事：“从前有座山，山中有座庙，庙里有个老和尚，老和尚在给小和尚讲故事：“从前有座山，山中有座庙，庙里有个老和尚，老和尚在给小和尚讲故事：“从前有座山，山中有座庙，庙里有个老和尚，老和尚在给小和尚讲故事：“太困了不讲了”，于是都回去睡觉了。”于是都回去睡觉了。”于是都回去睡觉了。”于是都回去睡觉了。</p></blockquote><figure><img src="./img/photos/recursion.jpeg" alt="Abstract" /><figcaption aria-hidden="true">Abstract</figcaption></figure><hr /><p>So why some engineers like to ues recursion instead of iteration?What's more, recursion can result in stack overflows and extremelyunstable time complexity(This can sometimes be a disaster).</p><p>One bad apple won't spoil the whole bunch. Recursive program featuresinclude elegance, inverse and recursive relationships</p><p><strong>Elegence</strong>: If you use recursion well, you can reducewhat shit-mountain you write. It can make people to know what you writeeasily.</p><p><strong>Inverse</strong>: Since the recursive caller needs tomaintain the call stack, and the stack has the characteristics oflast-in, first-out, the recursive program is suitable for meeting therequirements of the negation class.</p><p><strong>Recursive relationship</strong>: This can sometimes be a goodinterpretation of mathematical induction (finding the original term andlisting the recursive).</p><hr /><p><strong>How do we use recursion to solve some interesting problem?Let's see some examples.</strong></p><p><strong><em>Question 1: the sum of any one-digit non-negative numberis that number.</em></strong></p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="keyword">def</span> <span class="title function_">sum_digit_number</span>(<span class="params">n</span>):</span><br><span class="line">    <span class="keyword">if</span> n &lt; <span class="number">10</span>: <span class="comment">#Base Case</span></span><br><span class="line">        <span class="keyword">return</span> n</span><br><span class="line">    <span class="keyword">else</span>:      <span class="comment">#Recursive Case</span></span><br><span class="line">        <span class="keyword">return</span> n % <span class="number">10</span> + sum_digit_number(n // <span class="number">10</span>)</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p><strong><em>Question 2: The factorial of a number is defined as <spanclass="math inline">\(n! .\)</span></em></strong></p><figure class="highlight c"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br><span class="line">7</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="type">int</span> <span class="title function_">fact</span><span class="params">(<span class="type">int</span> n)</span></span><br><span class="line">&#123;</span><br><span class="line">    <span class="keyword">if</span> (n == <span class="number">0</span>)</span><br><span class="line">        <span class="keyword">return</span> <span class="number">1</span></span><br><span class="line">    <span class="keyword">else</span></span><br><span class="line">        <span class="keyword">return</span> n * fact(n - <span class="number">1</span>)</span><br><span class="line">&#125;</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><h3 id="summery"><em>Summery</em></h3><p>If we want to solve recursive problem, we should find <strong>Basecase</strong> , <strong>Recursive Case</strong> and <strong>Conditionalstatement</strong>. &gt; <strong>Base case</strong>: Evaluated without arecursive call (the smallest subproblem).</p><blockquote><p><strong>Recursive case</strong>: Evaluated with a recursive call(breaking down the problem further)</p></blockquote><blockquote><p><strong>Conditional statement</strong> to decide if it's a basecase</p></blockquote><hr /><h3 id="recursion-and-iteration"><em>Recursion and Iteration</em></h3><p><strong>Using recursion:</strong> <figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="keyword">def</span> <span class="title function_">fact</span>(<span class="params">n</span>):</span><br><span class="line">  <span class="keyword">if</span> n == <span class="number">0</span>:</span><br><span class="line">    <span class="keyword">return</span> <span class="number">1</span></span><br><span class="line">  <span class="keyword">else</span>:</span><br><span class="line">    <span class="keyword">return</span> n * fact(n-<span class="number">1</span>)</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure> <strong>Usingiteration:</strong> <figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br><span class="line">7</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="keyword">def</span> <span class="title function_">fact</span>(<span class="params">n</span>):</span><br><span class="line">  total = <span class="number">1</span></span><br><span class="line">  k = <span class="number">1</span></span><br><span class="line">  <span class="keyword">while</span> k &lt;= n:</span><br><span class="line">    total *= k</span><br><span class="line">    k += <span class="number">1</span></span><br><span class="line">  <span class="keyword">return</span> total</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure> What's more, we can express them usingmathematical language.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Using recursion:</strong> <strong><em><spanclass="math inline">\(n! = \left\{ \begin{aligned} 1\ \ if n == 0\\ n\cdot (n - 1)!\ \ otherwise \end{aligned}\right.\)</span></em></strong></p></blockquote><blockquote><p><strong>Using iteration:</strong> <strong><em><spanclass="math inline">\(n! = \prod \limits_{i=1}^ni\)</span></em></strong></p></blockquote><p><strong>Can be tricky</strong>: Iteration is a special case ofrecursion. Figure out what state must be maintained by the iterativefunction.</p><p><strong>More formulaic</strong>: Iteration is a special case ofrecursion.The state of an iteration can be passed as arguments.</p><hr /><p>But this is not the end, we still have many question. For example,what is tree recursion and can we make recursion better?</p><p><strong>Listen to the next breakdown!!</strong></p>]]></content>
      
      
